var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Adaptive-Design","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"In an adaptive experiment, each measurement is chosen based on what you've learned so far. The algorithm loops: design → acquire → update posterior → repeat. This can outperform batch design when the optimal measurement locations depend on the (unknown) parameter values.","title":"Adaptive Design"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#The-model","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"The same exponential decay from the Batch Design example:\n\ny = A exp(-k  t) + varepsilon qquad varepsilon sim mathcalN(0 sigma^2)\n\nusing OptimalDesign\nusing CairoMakie\nusing ComponentArrays\nusing Distributions\nusing Random; Random.seed!(42) # hide\n\nfunction model(θ, x)\n    θ.A * exp(-θ.k * x.t)\nend\n\nθ_true = ComponentArray(A = 2.0, k = 42.0)\nσ = 0.1\nacquire(x) = model(θ_true, x) + σ * randn()\nnothing # hide","title":"The model"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Defining-the-design-problem","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"This time we add a per-measurement cost — short measurements are cheap (cost ≈ 1) and long measurements are more expensive (cost up to 1.5). The experiment will be controlled by a total budget rather than a fixed number of measurements:\n\nprob = DesignProblem(\n    model,\n    parameters = (A = LogUniform(0.1, 10), k = Uniform(1, 50)),\n    transformation = select(:k),\n    sigma = Returns(σ),\n    cost = x -> x.t + 1,\n)\n\ncandidates = candidate_grid(t = range(0.001, 0.5, length = 200))\nnothing # hide","title":"Defining the design problem"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Running-the-adaptive-experiment","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"run_adaptive takes a budget and loops until it is exhausted. At each step it calls design internally using the current posterior, acquires a measurement, and updates. With n_per_step = 1 the experiment is fully sequential — each observation informs the next.\n\nprior = Particles(prob, 5000)\n\nresult = run_adaptive(\n    prob, candidates, prior, acquire;\n    budget = 50.0,\n    headless = true, # hide\n)\nnothing # hide\n\nA live dashboard is displayed of the acquisition process and evolution of parameter estimates. This can also be saved as a gif or mp4 following acquisition:\n\nrecord_dashboard(result, prob; filename=\"dashboard.gif\")\nnothing # hide\n\n(Image: Acquisition dashboard)","title":"Running the adaptive experiment"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Batch-comparison","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"For a fair comparison, we design a batch experiment with the same budget. Since both use cost-aware design, the difference is purely whether the design adapts to incoming data:\n\nresult_batch = run_batch(prob, candidates, prior, acquire;\n    budget = 50.0)\nnothing # hide","title":"Batch comparison"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Convergence","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"plot_convergence shows how the parameter estimates evolve as observations accumulate. The shaded band is ± 1 posterior standard deviation; the dashed line marks the true value:\n\nplot_convergence(result; truth = θ_true)","title":"Convergence"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Credible-bands","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"plot_credible_bands(prob, result, result_batch;\n    labels = [\"Adaptive\", \"Batch\"], truth = θ_true)","title":"Credible bands"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Corner-plot-—-adaptive-vs-batch","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"plot_corner(result, result_batch;\n    labels = [\"Adaptive\", \"Batch\"], truth = θ_true)","title":"Corner plot — adaptive vs batch"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/adaptive_design/#Posterior-evolution","page":"Adaptive Design","text":"With record_posterior = true, you can create an animation of the posterior evolving as observations arrive:\n\nrecord_corner_animation(result.log, \"posterior_evolution.gif\";\n    truth = θ_true, framerate = 3)\nnothing # hide\n\n(Image: Posterior evolution)","title":"Posterior evolution"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#Defining-Problems","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A DesignProblem bundles everything the design algorithm needs to know: the model, the noise structure, prior parameter uncertainty, what you want to learn, and any cost constraints.","title":"Defining Problems"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#Minimal-example","page":"Defining Problems","text":"prob = DesignProblem(\n    (θ, x) -> θ.A * exp(-θ.R₂ * x.t),\n    parameters = (A = LogUniform(0.1, 10), R₂ = Uniform(1, 50)),\n    sigma = Returns(0.1),\n)\n\nThe only required arguments are the prediction function and parameters. Everything else has sensible defaults.","title":"Minimal example"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#Constructor-arguments","page":"Defining Problems","text":"","title":"Constructor arguments"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#predict-(positional,-required)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A function (θ, x) -> y mapping parameters θ and design point x to a predicted observation. Both θ and x are accessed by named fields.\n\nScalar output:\n\n(θ, x) -> θ.A * exp(-θ.R₂ * x.t)\n\nVector output (multiple simultaneous observables):\n\n(θ, x) -> [θ.A₁ * exp(-θ.R₂₁ * x.t),\n            θ.A₂ * exp(-θ.R₂₂ * x.t)]","title":"predict (positional, required)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#parameters-(keyword,-required)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A NamedTuple of Distributions.Distribution objects specifying the prior on each parameter:\n\nparameters = (A = LogUniform(0.1, 10), R₂ = Uniform(1, 50))\n\nThe parameter names define the fields available on θ inside predict and sigma. Any distribution from Distributions.jl works.","title":"parameters (keyword, required)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#sigma-(keyword,-default:-constant-1)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A callable (θ, x) -> σ giving the noise standard deviation. Can depend on both parameters and design point. For constant noise, use Returns(σ):\n\nsigma = Returns(0.1)                       # constant noise\nsigma = (θ, x) -> 0.05 * abs(θ.A)         # signal-dependent noise\nsigma = Returns([0.1, 0.2])               # constant vector noise (for vector models)\nsigma = (θ, x) -> [0.1, 0.2]              # vector noise that could depend on θ, x\n\nFor vector models, sigma should return a vector of the same length as predict.","title":"sigma (keyword, default: constant 1)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#transformation-(keyword,-default:-Identity())","page":"Defining Problems","text":"Controls which parameters you want to estimate precisely.\n\nIdentity() — full D-optimality over all parameters (default)\nselect(:R₂) — Ds-optimality for a single parameter\nselect(:R₂₁, :R₂₂) — Ds-optimality for a subset\n\nselect constructs a DeltaMethod transformation that projects the Fisher information onto the parameters of interest.","title":"transformation (keyword, default: Identity())"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#criterion-(keyword,-default:-DCriterion())","page":"Defining Problems","text":"The optimality criterion:\n\nCriterion Objective Interpretation\nDCriterion() maximise log det(M) minimise volume of confidence ellipsoid\nACriterion() maximise -tr(M⁻¹) minimise average variance\nECriterion() maximise λ_min(M) minimise worst-case variance","title":"criterion (keyword, default: DCriterion())"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#jacobian-(keyword,-default:-nothing)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"An optional analytic Jacobian (θ, x) -> J where J is a 1×p matrix (scalar model) or m×p matrix (vector model). If omitted, the Jacobian is computed automatically via ForwardDiff.\n\njacobian = (θ, x) -> begin\n    e = exp(-θ.R₂ * x.t)\n    [θ.A * x.t * e   -θ.A * e]   # [∂y/∂A  ∂y/∂R₂]  — but transposed to 1×2\nend\n\nProviding an analytic Jacobian avoids automatic differentiation overhead and can be significantly faster for models evaluated many times.","title":"jacobian (keyword, default: nothing)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#cost-(keyword,-default:-constant-1)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A function x -> Real giving the cost of a single measurement at design point x:\n\ncost = x -> x.t + 1        # longer measurements cost more\ncost = Returns(1.0)         # unit cost (default)\n\nCost is used by run_adaptive to track budget consumption and by design for budget-aware allocation. When you pass budget instead of n to design, the number of measurements is determined automatically from the costs.","title":"cost (keyword, default: constant 1)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#switching_cost-(keyword,-default:-nothing)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A tuple (:field, value) specifying a fixed cost incurred when a discrete design variable changes value between consecutive measurements:\n\nswitching_cost = (:channel, 50.0)   # costs 50 to switch channels\n\nThis creates a SwitchingDesignProblem instead of a plain DesignProblem. The switching cost is added on top of the per-measurement cost whenever the named field changes. See the Switching Costs example.","title":"switching_cost (keyword, default: nothing)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#constraint-(keyword,-default:-always-true)","page":"Defining Problems","text":"A function (x, θ) -> Bool that restricts the design space. Only candidates where the constraint returns true are considered:\n\nconstraint = (x, θ) -> x.dose ≤ θ.max_dose   # parameter-dependent constraint","title":"constraint (keyword, default: always true)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/problems/#Candidates","page":"Defining Problems","text":"Design points are represented as NamedTuples. Use candidate_grid to generate the full outer product from named ranges:\n\njulia> using OptimalDesign\n\njulia> candidate_grid(t = [0.1, 0.2, 0.3])\n3-element Vector{@NamedTuple{t::Float64}}:\n (t = 0.1,)\n (t = 0.2,)\n (t = 0.3,)\n\njulia> candidate_grid(channel = [1, 2], t = [0.1, 0.2])\n4-element Vector{@NamedTuple{channel::Int64, t::Float64}}:\n (channel = 1, t = 0.1)\n (channel = 2, t = 0.1)\n (channel = 1, t = 0.2)\n (channel = 2, t = 0.2)\n\nThe field names in candidates must match what your predict function expects on x.","title":"Candidates"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#Switching-Costs","page":"Switching Costs","text":"warning: Experimental\nThe switching-cost API is experimental and may change in future releases.\n\nIn many experiments, changing measurement configuration is expensive — switching an instrument channel, moving a sample, or recalibrating. OptimalDesign.jl models this with a switching cost: a fixed penalty incurred whenever a discrete design variable changes value between consecutive measurements.","title":"Switching Costs"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#The-model","page":"Switching Costs","text":"Two exponential decays, selectively measured via a discrete control variable i in 1 2:\n\ny = A_i exp(-k_i  t) + varepsilon\n\nEach measurement observes one decay (chosen by i). Switching between decays costs 20 budget units.\n\nusing OptimalDesign\nusing CairoMakie\nusing ComponentArrays\nusing Distributions\nusing Random; Random.seed!(42) # hide\n\nfunction model(θ, x)\n    if x.i == 1\n        θ.A₁ * exp(-θ.k₁ * x.t)\n    else\n        θ.A₂ * exp(-θ.k₂ * x.t)\n    end\nend\n\nθ_true = ComponentArray(A₁ = 0.7, k₁ = 10.0, A₂ = 1.5, k₂ = 40.0)\nσ = 0.05\nacquire(x) = model(θ_true, x) + σ * randn()\nnothing # hide","title":"The model"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#Defining-the-design-problem","page":"Switching Costs","text":"The switching_cost = (:i, 20.0) tells the algorithm that changing the value of x.i between consecutive measurements costs 20, on top of the per-measurement cost. The candidates span both channels and a range of times:\n\nprob = DesignProblem(\n    model,\n    parameters = (\n        A₁ = Normal(1, 0.1),    k₁ = LogUniform(1, 50),\n        A₂ = Normal(1, 0.1),    k₂ = LogUniform(1, 50)),\n    transformation = select(:k₁, :k₂),\n    sigma = Returns(σ),\n    cost = x -> x.t + 1,\n    switching_cost = (:i, 20.0),\n)\n\ncandidates = candidate_grid(i = [1, 2], t = range(0.001, 0.5, length = 200))\nnothing # hide","title":"Defining the design problem"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#Running-the-adaptive-experiment","page":"Switching Costs","text":"With n_per_step > 1, the algorithm uses a receding-horizon strategy:\n\nPlan: compute an optimal batch design for the entire remaining budget using the exchange algorithm, accounting for accumulated information from prior observations\nSequence: reorder the design to minimise switching costs (via TSP over the support points)\nExecute: take the first n_per_step measurements, apportioned proportionally within each group to preserve time-point diversity\nUpdate: update the posterior with the new observations, then repeat from step 1\n\nThis amortises the switching cost — the algorithm allocates a block of measurements on one channel before switching, rather than reconsidering the channel at every single step. We also use a larger number of particles for the prior/posterior reflecting the increased number of parameters:\n\nprior = Particles(prob, 10000)\n\nresult = run_adaptive(\n    prob, candidates, prior, acquire;\n    budget = 200.0,\n    n_per_step = 10,\n    headless = true, # hide\n)\n\nrecord_dashboard(result, prob; filename=\"switching_dashboard.gif\") # hide\nnothing # hide\n\nA live dashboard is displayed of the acquisition process and evolution of parameter estimates:\n\n(Image: Acquisition dashboard)","title":"Running the adaptive experiment"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#Convergence","page":"Switching Costs","text":"The convergence plot shows both rates being learned simultaneously, with uncertainty decreasing as data accumulates:\n\nplot_convergence(result; truth = θ_true, params = [:k₁, :k₂])","title":"Convergence"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#Corner-plot","page":"Switching Costs","text":"plot_corner(result; truth = θ_true)","title":"Corner plot"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/switching_costs/#Posterior-evolution","page":"Switching Costs","text":"record_corner_animation(result.log, \"switching_posterior.gif\";\n    params = [:k₁, :k₂],\n    truth = θ_true, framerate = 3)\nnothing # hide\n\n(Image: Posterior evolution)","title":"Posterior evolution"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Posterior-Inference","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"OptimalDesign.jl uses a particle filter to represent parameter uncertainty. A Particles is a weighted set of parameter samples — initially drawn from the prior, then reweighted as data arrives.","title":"Posterior Inference"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Creating-a-prior","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"prior = Particles(prob, 1000)\n\nThis draws 1000 particles from the prior distributions specified in prob.parameters. All particles start with equal weight.\n\nMore particles give better coverage of the prior but cost more in design computation.","title":"Creating a prior"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Updating-with-data","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"After acquiring observations, the posterior is updated via run_batch or run_adaptive. These functions do not mutate the prior — they make an internal copy and return a result containing both the original prior and the updated posterior. Under the hood, they call update!, which:\n\nComputes the likelihood of each observation under each particle\nUses likelihood tempering to gradually increase the data weight, avoiding particle collapse\nResamples and applies a Liu–West kernel when the effective sample size drops too low\n\nYou don't need to call update! directly — run_batch and run_adaptive handle it.","title":"Updating with data"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Extracting-estimates","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"","title":"Extracting estimates"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Point-estimate","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"μ = mean(result.posterior)\n# μ.A ≈ 1.0, μ.R₂ ≈ 25.0\n\n# Or directly on the result:\nμ = mean(result)\n\nReturns a ComponentArray with the weighted mean of each parameter.","title":"Point estimate"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Effective-sample-size","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"ess = effective_sample_size(result.posterior)\n\nThe ESS measures how many \"independent\" particles the posterior effectively contains. If ESS drops very low (e.g., below 50), the posterior may be poorly represented. The package automatically resamples when this happens during updates.","title":"Effective sample size"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#Predictions-and-credible-bands","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"To propagate posterior uncertainty through the model:\n\n# Predict at a grid of design points\ngrid = candidate_grid(t = range(0, 0.5, length = 100))\npreds = posterior_predictions(prob, result.posterior, grid; n_samples = 200)\n\npreds is a matrix (rows = grid points, columns = posterior samples) for scalar models, or a vector of matrices for vector models.\n\nTo compute quantile-based credible bands:\n\nband = credible_band(preds; level = 0.9)\n# band.lower, band.median, band.upper — vectors over the grid\n\nThese can be plotted directly or passed to plot_credible_bands (see Plotting).","title":"Predictions and credible bands"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/posteriors/#How-likelihood-tempering-works","page":"Posterior Inference","text":"When many observations arrive at once (as in run_batch), a naive likelihood update would concentrate all weight on a handful of particles, effectively collapsing the posterior. OptimalDesign avoids this with adaptive tempering:\n\nThe full likelihood L(theta) is raised to a power beta, starting at beta = 0\nbeta is increased in steps, each time choosing the largest Deltabeta that keeps the ESS above a threshold (default: 50% of particle count)\nBetween steps, particles are resampled and jittered using a Liu–West kernel to maintain diversity\nThe process continues until beta = 1, at which point the full likelihood has been absorbed\n\nThis is equivalent to sequential Monte Carlo (SMC) with an adaptive tempering schedule. It works for both batch and single-observation updates — even a single very informative observation can benefit from tempering.","title":"How likelihood tempering works"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#API","page":"API","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.ACriterion","page":"API","text":"ACriterion()\n\nA-optimal design criterion: maximises -tr(M⁻¹), i.e. minimises the average variance of the parameter estimates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.ACriterion"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.AbstractExperimentResult","page":"API","text":"AbstractExperimentResult\n\nSupertype for experiment results. Subtypes: BatchResult, AdaptiveResult. All results carry .prior, .posterior, and .observations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.AbstractExperimentResult"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.AbstractPosterior","page":"API","text":"AbstractPosterior\n\nSupertype for posterior representations. Currently the only concrete subtype is Particles.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.AbstractPosterior"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.AdaptiveResult","page":"API","text":"AdaptiveResult\n\nResult of run_adaptive. Contains prior, posterior, log, and observations. The log field is an ExperimentLog with per-step diagnostics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.AdaptiveResult"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.BatchResult","page":"API","text":"BatchResult\n\nResult of run_batch. Contains prior, posterior, design, and observations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.BatchResult"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.DCriterion","page":"API","text":"DCriterion()\n\nD-optimal design criterion: maximises log(det(M)), the log-determinant of the (transformed) Fisher information matrix. Equivalent to minimising the volume of the confidence ellipsoid.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.DCriterion"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.DesignProblem-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","text":"DesignProblem(predict; kwargs...)\n\nConstruct a design problem. Returns DesignProblem or SwitchingDesignProblem depending on whether switching_cost is provided.\n\njacobian: (θ, x) -> J matrix, or nothing for ForwardDiff (default: nothing)\nsigma: (θ, x) -> noise (default: Returns(1.0)). For constant noise, use Returns(σ)\nparameters: NamedTuple of prior distributions (required)\ntransformation: defaults to Identity()\ncriterion: design criterion (default: DCriterion())\ncost: x -> Real, per-measurement cost (default: Returns(1.0))\nswitching_cost: nothing or (:param, value) — fixed cost when switching param (default: nothing)\nconstraint: (x, θ) -> Bool (default: (x, θ) -> true)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.DesignProblem"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.ECriterion","page":"API","text":"ECriterion()\n\nE-optimal design criterion: maximises the minimum eigenvalue of M, i.e. minimises the worst-case variance direction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.ECriterion"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.ExperimentLog","page":"API","text":"ExperimentLog\n\nStores the history of an adaptive experiment: design points, observations, costs, and diagnostics for each step. Created internally by run_adaptive.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.ExperimentLog"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.ExperimentalDesign","page":"API","text":"ExperimentalDesign{T}\n\nAn experimental design: a list of (design_point, count) pairs specifying how many measurements to make at each design point. Iterable, indexable, and displayable.\n\nConstruct via design or directly from a vector of (NamedTuple, Int) pairs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.ExperimentalDesign"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.OptimalityResult","page":"API","text":"OptimalityResult\n\nResult of verify_optimality. Fields: is_optimal, max_derivative, dimension, gateaux (derivative at each candidate), and candidates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.OptimalityResult"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.Particles-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"Particles(prob::AbstractDesignProblem, n::Int)\n\nConstruct a Particles by drawing n particles from the prior. All particles have equal weight.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.Particles"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.SwitchingDesignProblem","page":"API","text":"SwitchingDesignProblem\n\nA design problem with switching costs between levels of a discrete control variable. Created automatically by DesignProblem(...) when switching_cost is specified.\n\nwarning: Experimental\nThe switching-cost API may change in future releases.\n\nSee also: DesignProblem\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.SwitchingDesignProblem"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._average_criterion-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API","text":"Compute the average criterion value Eθ[Φ(Mτ(w,θ))] for a given weight vector.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._average_criterion"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._bisect_Δβ-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Float64, Float64}","page":"API","text":"Bisect for the largest Δβ ∈ (0, remaining] such that trial ESS ≥ target. If even Δβ = remaining keeps ESS above target, return remaining (finish in one step).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._bisect_Δβ"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._compress-Tuple{Vector{<:NamedTuple}}","page":"API","text":"Compress a list of selected candidates into (x, count) pairs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._compress"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._compute_fw_gap-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API","text":"Compute FW gap without side effects.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._compute_fw_gap"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._compute_total_ll-Tuple{Particles, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}}","page":"API","text":"Compute total log-likelihood of all data for each particle.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._compute_total_ll"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._d_sensitivity_matrix-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"For D-optimality with Identity: C = M⁻¹ For Ds-optimality with DeltaMethod: C = M⁻¹ ∇τ' Mτ ∇τ M⁻¹\n\nIn both cases, d(x) = tr(C M(x)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._d_sensitivity_matrix"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._deduct_switching_overhead-Tuple{DesignProblem, Any, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"No switching overhead for plain DesignProblem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._deduct_switching_overhead"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._deduct_switching_overhead-Tuple{OptimalDesign.SwitchingDesignProblem, Any, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"Estimate switching overhead and deduct from budget.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._deduct_switching_overhead"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._default_grid-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}}","page":"API","text":"Generate a dense 1D grid from observations, spanning the range of the first continuous field.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._default_grid"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._draw_corner_data!-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API","text":"_draw_corner_data!(fig, axes_grid, datasets, names, truth_vals; bins, cs, ls)\n\nRender corner plot data into an existing figure/axes grid. Each dataset is (vals, weights) where vals[param_idx][particle_idx]. Clears axes before drawing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._draw_corner_data!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._est_total_steps-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"Estimate total steps from current pace.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._est_total_steps"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._format_design_point-Tuple{NamedTuple}","page":"API","text":"Format a design point NamedTuple for compact display.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._format_design_point"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._format_params-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","text":"Format a parameter ComponentArray for compact display.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._format_params"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._get_particles-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"Extract particles from posterior (supports Particles or plain Vector). When resample=true, draws from the posterior proportional to weights so that a uniform average over the returned particles is correct.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._get_particles"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._initialise_weights-NTuple{5, Any}","page":"API","text":"Initialise exchange weights with a robust set of support points.\n\nFalls back to evenly-spaced points when single-point utilities are not computable (e.g., rank-deficient FIM under DeltaMethod).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._initialise_weights"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._interest_params-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","text":"_interest_params(prob) → Vector{Symbol}\n\nExtract the parameter names of interest from the design problem's transformation. Falls back to all parameter names if no selection is available.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._interest_params"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._make_corner_axes-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"_make_corner_axes(fig, names)\n\nCreate the d×d grid of axes for a corner plot. Returns axes_grid matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._make_corner_axes"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._merge_nearby!-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"_merge_nearby!(weights, candidates; rtol=0.05)\n\nMerge nearby support points based on normalised distance in design space.\n\nFor each pair of support points closer than rtol (relative to the range of each continuous dimension), consolidate weight onto the heavier point. Discrete (non-numeric) fields must match exactly — points differing in any discrete field are never merged regardless of distance.\n\nWorks correctly for:\n\nNon-uniform grids (logarithmic, etc.)\nMultidimensional design spaces (e.g., (t=..., dose=...))\nMixed continuous/discrete variables\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._merge_nearby!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._min_switching_order-Tuple{OptimalDesign.SwitchingDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"Find the permutation of support points that minimises total switching cost. Brute-force for n ≤ 8 (≤ 40320 perms), nearest-neighbour for larger.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._min_switching_order"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._param_transforms-Tuple{NamedTuple}","page":"API","text":"_param_transforms(parameters::NamedTuple)\n\nDerive (forward, inverse) transform pairs from prior distributions. Forward maps to unconstrained space; inverse maps back.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._param_transforms"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._particle_weighted_fim-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API","text":"Build the weighted FIM for a single particle θ: Mw(θ) = Σk wk Mk(θ). Returns a p×p matrix in the full parameter space (no transformation).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._particle_weighted_fim"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._scalar_obs-Tuple{Real}","page":"API","text":"Extract a scalar from a possibly structured observation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._scalar_obs"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._select_batch-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API","text":"Batch selection via exchange algorithm with cost awareness.\n\nWhen per-measurement costs vary, the FIM is weighted by wₖ/cₖ so the exchange algorithm prefers candidates that are informative per unit cost. For SwitchingDesignProblem, the output is sequenced to minimise switching.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._select_batch"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._select_greedy-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API","text":"Greedy sequential selection: pick the best candidate, add its FIM to a running total, then pick the next based on marginal gain.\n\nWhen n=1 (adaptive case), this is a simple argmax of utility/cost. When n>1, the accumulated FIM ensures each successive pick adds complementary information rather than repeating the same candidate.\n\nPrecomputes all per-particle FIMs to avoid redundant ForwardDiff calls.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._select_greedy"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._sequence_design-Tuple{DesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"No-op sequencing for plain DesignProblem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._sequence_design"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._sequence_design-Tuple{OptimalDesign.SwitchingDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"Reorder (x, count) pairs to minimise total switching cost.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._sequence_design"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._snapshot_posterior-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"_snapshot_posterior(posterior::Particles)\n\nDeep-copy the current posterior state for history recording.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._snapshot_posterior"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._snapshot_to_dataset-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"_snapshot_to_dataset(snapshot, names)\n\nConvert a posterior snapshot (particles, log_weights) to (vals, weights) for plotting.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._snapshot_to_dataset"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._take_first-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{ExperimentalDesign{T}, Int64}} where T","page":"API","text":"_take_first(ξ::ExperimentalDesign, n::Int; switching_param=nothing) → ExperimentalDesign\n\nExtract the first n measurements from a design.\n\nWhen switching_param is provided, measurements are apportioned proportionally within each contiguous group block (identified by switching_param value), preserving the time-point diversity of the exchange algorithm's allocation. Without switching_param, simply takes the first n in sequence order.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._take_first"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._transformed_dimension-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","text":"Dimension q of the parameter space of interest. For D-optimality, the GEQ bound is d(x) ≤ q at all candidates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._transformed_dimension"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._trial_ess-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Float64}","page":"API","text":"Compute ESS that would result from adding Δβ * totalll to logweights, without modifying them.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._trial_ess"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._tsp_brute_force!-NTuple{7, Any}","page":"API","text":"Recursive brute-force TSP over support points.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._tsp_brute_force!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._update_design_2d!-Tuple{OptimalDesign.LiveDashboard, Any, Symbol, Symbol}","page":"API","text":"Rebuild the 2D design scatter with marker sizes proportional to visit count.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._update_design_2d!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._update_posterior_panel!-Tuple{OptimalDesign.LiveDashboard, Any}","page":"API","text":"Redraw posterior marginal histograms for interest parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._update_posterior_panel!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._weighted_objective-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API","text":"Compute the weighted objective: Eθ[Φ(Mprior(θ) + Σk (wk/ck) Mk(θ))].\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._weighted_objective"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign._weighted_sample_indices-Tuple{AbstractVector, Int64}","page":"API","text":"Systematic resampling of n indices proportional to weights (for plotting).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign._weighted_sample_indices"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.apportion-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:Real}, Int64}","page":"API","text":"apportion(weights, n)\n\nConvert continuous weights to integer counts summing to n.\n\nUses the largest remainder method (Hamilton's method):\n\nFloor each weight * n\nDistribute remaining counts to candidates with largest fractional parts.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.apportion"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.apportion-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:Real}, Real, AbstractVector{<:Real}}","page":"API","text":"apportion(weights, budget, costs)\n\nBudget-aware apportionment: convert continuous budget-fraction weights to integer measurement counts given per-point costs.\n\nPoint k gets budget * weights[k] / costs[k] ideal measurements. Uses largest-remainder rounding, checking that each additional measurement fits within the budget.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.apportion"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.candidate_grid-Tuple{}","page":"API","text":"candidate_grid(; kwargs...)\n\nGenerate candidate design points from keyword arguments. Each keyword maps a design variable name to a collection of values; the result is the full outer product as a vector of NamedTuples.\n\nExamples\n\ncandidate_grid(t = range(0, 0.5, length=200))\n# → [(t=0.0,), (t=0.0025,), ..., (t=0.5,)]\n\ncandidate_grid(t = range(0, 0.5, 50), dose = [1, 10, 100])\n# → [(t=0.0, dose=1), (t=0.0, dose=10), ..., (t=0.5, dose=100)]\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.candidate_grid"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.credible_band-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"API","text":"credible_band(predictions; level=0.9)\n\nCompute credible band from posterior predictions. Returns (lower, median, upper) vectors.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.credible_band"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.cumulative_cost-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"cumulative_cost(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nCompute the cumulative cost at each step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.cumulative_cost"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.design-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Any}","page":"API","text":"design(problem, candidates, posterior; n=1, budget=Inf, kwargs...)\n\nCompute an optimal experimental design: determine which design points to measure and how many times.\n\nReturns an ExperimentalDesign with (x, count) pairs.\n\nSpecify the experiment size via n (number of measurements) or budget (total cost). When budget is finite and n is not specified, the number of measurements is determined automatically from the budget and per-measurement costs.\n\nFor large n, uses the exchange algorithm for weight optimisation. For small n, uses greedy marginal-gain selection.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nn: number of measurements to allocate (default: inferred from budget if budget is finite, otherwise 1)\nbudget = Inf: total cost budget\nposterior_samples = 0: number of posterior samples for utility evaluation\nx_prev = nothing: previous design point (for cost computation)\nexchange_algorithm = (n > 5): if true, use exchange algorithm for weight optimisation\nexchange_steps = 100: iterations for exchange algorithm\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.design"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.design_points-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"design_points(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nExtract all design points from the experiment log.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.design_points"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.draw-Tuple{NamedTuple, Int64}","page":"API","text":"draw(parameters::NamedTuple, n::Int)\n\nDraw n samples from the prior, returning a Vector of ComponentArrays.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.draw"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.draw-Tuple{NamedTuple}","page":"API","text":"draw(parameters::NamedTuple)\n\nDraw a single sample from the prior, returning a ComponentArray.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.draw"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.effective_sample_size-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"effective_sample_size(posterior::Particles)\n\nCompute the effective sample size (ESS) of the weighted particles.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.effective_sample_size"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.efficiency-Tuple{ExperimentalDesign, ExperimentalDesign, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Particles}","page":"API","text":"efficiency(ξ_a, ξ_b, prob, candidates, posterior; kwargs...)\n\nRelative efficiency of design ξ_a vs design ξ_b.\n\nFor D-optimality: (det Ma / det Mb)^(1/q) where q = dimension of interest. Efficiency > 1 means ξa is better; < 1 means ξb is better.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.efficiency"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.exchange-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"exchange(prob, candidates, particles; kwargs...)\n\nTwo-phase Frank-Wolfe algorithm for batch weight optimisation on a discrete candidate grid, following the approach of Yang, Biedermann & Tang (2013).\n\nPhase 1 (Discovery): Pairwise Frank-Wolfe to find approximate support. Uses adaptive smoothness estimation for step sizes (à la Kirstine.jl).\n\nPhase 2 (Refinement): Fix the support set found in Phase 1 and run another round of pairwise FW restricted to those points.\n\nReturns a weight vector (length = number of candidates) that sums to 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.exchange"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.expected_utility-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector, Any}","page":"API","text":"expected_utility(prob, particles, x; posterior_samples=50)\n\nCompute the expected utility of design point x by Monte Carlo over posterior particles. Uses the criterion from prob.criterion.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.expected_utility"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.gateaux_derivative-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Particles, ExperimentalDesign}","page":"API","text":"gateaux_derivative(prob, candidates, posterior, design; kwargs...)\n\nCompute the Gateaux derivative of the expected design criterion at each candidate, for a design with the given weights.\n\nFor D-optimality (Identity):  d(x) = tr(M⁻¹ M(x)) For Ds-optimality (DeltaMethod): d(x) = tr(C M(x)) where C = M⁻¹ ∇τ' Mτ ∇τ M⁻¹\n\nFor A/E criteria, numerical differentiation is used.\n\nReturns a vector of derivatives (one per candidate).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.gateaux_derivative"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.has_posterior_history-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"has_posterior_history(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nCheck whether the log contains posterior snapshots for animation/replay.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.has_posterior_history"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.information!-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"information!(M, prob, θ, x; cache=nothing)\n\nIn-place version: compute the FIM and write result into pre-allocated matrix M. Accepts an optional GradientCache to avoid allocating ForwardDiff config each call.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.information!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.information-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"information(prob, θ, x)\n\nCompute the Fisher Information Matrix at (θ, x) for the given DesignProblem.\n\nDispatches on whether an analytic Jacobian is provided or ForwardDiff is used.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.information"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.log_evidence_series-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"log_evidence_series(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nExtract the series of log marginal likelihood values (sequential model checking).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.log_evidence_series"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.loglikelihood-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Any, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"loglikelihood(prob::AbstractDesignProblem, θ, x, y)\n\nLog-likelihood of observation y at (θ, x) under the noise model defined by prob.sigma.\n\nHandles scalar, vector, and structured observations (NamedTuple with :value and :σ).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.loglikelihood"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.n_obs-Tuple{ExperimentalDesign}","page":"API","text":"n_obs(ξ::ExperimentalDesign)\n\nTotal number of measurements in the design.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.n_obs"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.observation_diagnostics-Tuple{Particles, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"observation_diagnostics(posterior, prob, x, y)\n\nScore an observation against the current posterior to detect model deviations.\n\nReturns (mean_residual, log_marginal):\n\nmean_residual: posterior-weighted mean residual (y - ŷ)\nlog_marginal: log marginal likelihood p(y | data so far)\n\nA running series of log_marginal values constitutes sequential Bayesian model checking. Sharp drops indicate observations surprising under the current model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.observation_diagnostics"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.observations-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"observations(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nExtract all observations from the experiment log.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.observations"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_convergence-Tuple{AdaptiveResult}","page":"API","text":"plot_convergence(result::AdaptiveResult; kwargs...)\n\nPlot convergence from an AdaptiveResult. Convenience wrapper.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_convergence"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_convergence-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"plot_convergence(log::ExperimentLog; truth=nothing, params=nothing, x_axis=:obs)\n\nPlot the convergence of parameter estimates over the course of an adaptive experiment. Shows the posterior mean ± 1 standard deviation at each step.\n\nRequires record_posterior = true in run_adaptive.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\ntruth: true parameter values to overlay as dashed horizontal lines\nparams::Vector{Symbol}: which parameters to show (default: all)\nx_axis::Symbol: :obs for observation number, :cost for cumulative cost\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_convergence"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_corner-Tuple{Vararg{AbstractExperimentResult}}","page":"API","text":"plot_corner(result; truth=θ_true)\nplot_corner(result1, result2; labels=[\"Optimal\", \"Uniform\"], truth=θ_true)\n\nCorner plot from one or more experiment results.\n\nWith a single result, compares prior vs posterior. With multiple results, compares their posteriors.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_corner"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_corner-Tuple{Vararg{Particles}}","page":"API","text":"plot_corner(posteriors...; params, truth, labels, colors, bins, level)\n\nCorner plot (pair plot) showing 1D marginal histograms on the diagonal and 2D weighted scatter plots on the lower triangle.\n\nAccepts one or more Particles objects for overlay comparison (e.g. prior vs posterior, or optimal vs uniform).\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nparams::Vector{Symbol}: which parameters to show (default: all)\ntruth::Union{Nothing, NamedTuple, AbstractVector}: true parameter values to mark\nlabels::Vector{String}: legend labels for each posterior (default: \"1\", \"2\", …)\ncolors: color per posterior (default: blue, orange, green, …)\nbins::Int = 30: histogram bin count\nlevel::Real = 0.9: credible interval level for 1D marginals\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_corner"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_credible_bands-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:Particles}, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"plot_credible_bands(prob, posteriors, x_grid; labels, colors, truth, observations, ...)\n\nMulti-panel credible band plot comparing several posteriors (e.g. prior, optimal, uniform). Creates vertically stacked panels, one per posterior.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nlabels::Vector{String}: panel titles (default: \"1\", \"2\", …)\ncolors: band colour per panel (default: gray, blue, orange, …)\ntruth: callable or vector of true y-values to overlay as dashed red line\nobservations: vector of observation vectors (one per posterior, or nothing)\nlevel::Real = 0.9: credible interval level\nx_field::Symbol: which field of x to use as x-axis\nn_samples::Int = 200: posterior samples for prediction\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_credible_bands"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_credible_bands-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Particles, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"plot_credible_bands(prob, posterior, x_grid; level=0.9, observations=nothing)\n\nPlot posterior credible bands with optional observation overlay.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_credible_bands"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_credible_bands-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Vararg{AbstractExperimentResult}}","page":"API","text":"plot_credible_bands(prob, result; truth=θ_true)\nplot_credible_bands(prob, result1, result2; labels=[\"Optimal\", \"Uniform\"], truth=θ_true)\n\nPlot credible bands from one or more experiment results. The prior from the first result is shown as the first panel, followed by each result's posterior with its observations overlaid.\n\nThe prediction grid is inferred from observations by default. Pass x_grid to override.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_credible_bands"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_design_allocation-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"plot_design_allocation(candidates, weights; ...)\n\nPlot the weight distribution across candidates for a batch design. Auto-detects 1D (stem plot) vs 2D (scatter/bubble plot) design variables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_design_allocation"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_design_allocation-Tuple{ExperimentalDesign, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}}","page":"API","text":"plot_design_allocation(ξ::ExperimentalDesign, candidates; ...)\n\nPlot the weight distribution for an ExperimentalDesign.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_design_allocation"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_gateaux-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, AbstractVector, Any}","page":"API","text":"plot_gateaux(candidates, gd, p; ...)\n\nPlot the Gateaux derivative at each candidate, with the optimality bound. Auto-detects 1D (line plot) vs 2D (heatmap/scatter) design variables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_gateaux"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_gateaux-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Particles, ExperimentalDesign}","page":"API","text":"plot_gateaux(prob, candidates, posterior, ξ; kwargs...)\n\nCompute the Gateaux derivative and plot it in one call. Equivalent to plot_gateaux(verify_optimality(prob, candidates, posterior, ξ; kwargs...)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_gateaux"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_gateaux-Tuple{OptimalityResult}","page":"API","text":"plot_gateaux(r::OptimalityResult; kwargs...)\n\nPlot the Gateaux derivative from a verify_optimality result.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_gateaux"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_posterior_marginals-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"plot_posterior_marginals(posterior; params=nothing)\n\nPlot histogram of posterior marginals for each parameter. Kept for backward compatibility — see plot_corner for the full corner plot.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_posterior_marginals"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.plot_residuals-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"plot_residuals(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nPlot residual diagnostics from an experiment log.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.plot_residuals"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.posterior_predictions-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Particles, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"posterior_predictions(prob, posterior, x_grid; n_samples=200)\n\nGenerate posterior predictions over a grid of design points.\n\nFor scalar models, returns a Matrix{Float64} of size (n_samples, length(x_grid)). For vector models, returns a Vector{Matrix{Float64}} — one matrix per output component.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.posterior_predictions"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.posterior_snapshots-Tuple{ExperimentLog}","page":"API","text":"posterior_snapshots(log::ExperimentLog)\n\nReturn vector of (particles, log_weights) snapshots, one per observation step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.posterior_snapshots"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.record_corner_animation-Tuple{ExperimentLog, String}","page":"API","text":"record_corner_animation(log, filename; kwargs...)\n\nRecord an animation of the posterior evolving from prior through each observation. Requires record_posterior=true in run_adaptive.\n\nProduces an MP4 or GIF (determined by filename extension) using CairoMakie.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nparams::Vector{Symbol}: which parameters to show (default: all)\ntruth: true parameter values to mark with dashed crosshairs\nstep_interval::Int = 1: show every Nth step (default: every step)\nframerate::Int = 5: frames per second\nbins::Int = 30: histogram bin count\nprior_color = (:gray, 0.3): colour for the prior overlay\nposterior_color = (:royalblue, 0.6): colour for the current posterior\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.record_corner_animation"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.record_dashboard-Tuple{AdaptiveResult, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem}","page":"API","text":"record_dashboard(result, prob; kwargs...) → filename\n\nReplay an adaptive experiment as a dashboard animation and save to a GIF or MP4. This is useful for documentation — it produces the same dashboard layout as the live run_adaptive display but rendered offline via CairoMakie.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nfilename = \"dashboard.gif\": output path (extension determines format)\nduration = 5.0: target duration in seconds\nsize = (1200, 800): figure size in pixels\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.record_dashboard"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.resample!-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"resample!(posterior; prob=nothing, a=0.98)\n\nSystematic resampling with Liu-West kernel jittering.\n\nThe Liu-West filter shrinks each resampled particle toward the ensemble mean and adds correlated noise, calibrated to preserve the posterior's first two moments. When prob is provided, jittering operates in a transformed (unconstrained) space derived from the prior bounds, preventing particles from leaving the support.\n\nArguments\n\nprob: DesignProblem (optional). Provides prior distributions for bound-aware transforms.\na: shrinkage parameter (default 0.98). Controls jitter magnitude: h² = 1 - a².\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.resample!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.run_adaptive-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"run_adaptive(prob, candidates, prior, acquire; kwargs...) → AdaptiveResult\n\nRun an adaptive experiment: design → acquire → update, repeating until the budget is exhausted.\n\nThe prior is not mutated — a deep copy is made internally.\n\nKeyword arguments\n\nbudget: total cost budget (required)\nposterior_samples = 50: mini-batch for utility evaluation\nn_per_step = 1: measurements per adaptive step\nheadless = false: suppress GUI for testing\nprediction_grid = nothing: dense x grid for credible band plots\nrecord_posterior = true: snapshot posterior at every step for animation/replay\n\nReturns an AdaptiveResult with fields prior, posterior, log, observations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.run_adaptive"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.run_batch-Tuple{ExperimentalDesign, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"run_batch(ξ, prob, prior, acquire) → BatchResult\n\nExecute a pre-computed design: acquire observations and update the posterior.\n\nThe prior is not mutated — a deep copy is made internally.\n\nξ is an ExperimentalDesign from design() — iterate it to get (x, count) pairs. acquire is a callable x -> y that returns an observation.\n\nReturns a BatchResult with fields prior, posterior, design, observations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.run_batch"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.run_batch-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"run_batch(prob, candidates, prior, acquire; n=1, kwargs...) → BatchResult\n\nConvenience: compute an optimal design and execute it in one call. Equivalent to ξ = design(...); run_batch(ξ, prob, prior, acquire).\n\nPass n for a fixed number of measurements, or budget to let the number of measurements be determined by the cost structure.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.run_batch"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.safe_criterion-Tuple{DCriterion, AbstractMatrix}","page":"API","text":"safe_criterion(criterion, M) -> Float64\n\nEvaluate the design criterion on M, returning -Inf for singular/non-posdef matrices instead of throwing. Avoids try/catch in hot loops.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.safe_criterion"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.sample-Tuple{Particles, Int64}","page":"API","text":"sample(posterior::Particles, n::Int)\n\nDraw n particles from the posterior (with replacement, proportional to weights).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.sample"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.score_candidates-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Particles, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"score_candidates(prob, posterior, candidates; posterior_samples=50)\n\nScore all candidates by expected utility. Returns a vector of scores.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.score_candidates"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.select-Tuple{Vararg{Symbol}}","page":"API","text":"select(names::Symbol...)\n\nConvenience constructor for DeltaMethod that selects named parameters. Returns a function that extracts the named components from a ComponentArray.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.select"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.selected_parameters-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem}","page":"API","text":"selected_parameters(prob) → Union{Nothing, Tuple{Symbol...}}\n\nReturn the parameter names selected for estimation (via select(...)), or nothing if full D-optimality.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.selected_parameters"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.systematic_resample-Tuple{AbstractVector, Int64}","page":"API","text":"systematic_resample(weights, n)\n\nSystematic resampling: returns n indices sampled proportional to weights.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.systematic_resample"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.total_cost-Tuple{DesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"total_cost(prob, prev, x)\n\nTotal cost of measuring at x after prev, including any switching penalty.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.total_cost"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.transform-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractMatrix, Any}","page":"API","text":"transform(prob, M)\n\nApply the transformation to the information matrix.\n\nIdentity: returns M unchanged.\nDeltaMethod: computes [∇τ M⁻¹ ∇τ']⁻¹ via ForwardDiff.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.transform"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.uniform_allocation-Tuple{AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Int64}","page":"API","text":"uniform_allocation(candidates, n)\n\nAllocate n measurements uniformly spaced across the candidate list. Selects n evenly-spaced indices from the candidate vector. Returns Vector{Tuple{NamedTuple, Int}}.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.uniform_allocation"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.update!-Tuple{Particles, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}}","page":"API","text":"update!(posterior::Particles, prob::AbstractDesignProblem, data::AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple};\n        ess_threshold=0.5, a=0.95)\n\nBatch update using adaptive likelihood tempering (SMC sampler).\n\nComputes each particle's total log-likelihood across all data, then raises the tempering exponent β from 0 → 1 in adaptive steps. At each step, the step size Δβ is chosen by bisection so that the ESS stays just above ess_threshold × n, then particles are resampled with Liu-West jittering.\n\nEach element of data must have fields x (design point) and y (observation).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.update!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.update!-Tuple{Particles, OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"update!(posterior::Particles, prob::AbstractDesignProblem, x, y; ess_threshold=0.5, a=0.95)\n\nIncorporate observation y at design point x. Delegates to the batch method with adaptive tempering, so even a single highly informative observation is tempered in gracefully.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.update!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.verify_optimality-Tuple{OptimalDesign.AbstractDesignProblem, AbstractVector{<:NamedTuple}, Particles, ExperimentalDesign}","page":"API","text":"verify_optimality(prob, candidates, posterior, ξ; kwargs...) → OptimalityResult\n\nCheck the General Equivalence Theorem: at an optimal design, the Gateaux derivative should be ≤ q (dimension of interest) at all candidates, with equality at support points.\n\nReturns an OptimalityResult with fields is_optimal, max_derivative, dimension, gateaux (full derivative vector), and candidates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.verify_optimality"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.weighted_fim!-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, AbstractMatrix, Real}","page":"API","text":"weighted_fim!(M, J, σ)\n\nIn-place computation of J'Σ⁻¹J, writing result into M.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.weighted_fim!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.weighted_fim-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, Real}","page":"API","text":"weighted_fim(J, σ)\n\nCompute J'Σ⁻¹J from Jacobian J and noise specification σ.\n\nScalar σ: F = J'J / σ²\nVector σ: F = J' diag(1 ./ σ.²) J\nMatrix Σ: F = J' Σ⁻¹ J\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.weighted_fim"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#OptimalDesign.weights-Tuple{ExperimentalDesign, AbstractVector}","page":"API","text":"weights(ξ::ExperimentalDesign, candidates)\n\nConvert design allocation to a weight vector over the candidate set. Returns a vector of length length(candidates) summing to 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"OptimalDesign.weights"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Statistics.mean-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"mean(p::Particles)\n\nWeighted mean of the particles. Returns a ComponentArray with one entry per parameter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Statistics.mean"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Statistics.std-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"std(p::Particles)\n\nWeighted standard deviation of the particles. Returns a ComponentArray with one entry per parameter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Statistics.std"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Statistics.var-Tuple{Particles}","page":"API","text":"var(p::Particles)\n\nWeighted variance of the particles. Returns a ComponentArray with one entry per parameter.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Statistics.var"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#Theory","page":"Theory","text":"This page gives a concise overview of the ideas behind optimal experimental design. For a thorough treatment, see the references at the end.","title":"Theory"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#What-is-experimental-design?","page":"Theory","text":"An experiment measures a system at chosen conditions — a time point, a dose, a frequency, a temperature. The design is the set of conditions and how many times each is measured. A good design extracts as much information as possible from a limited measurement budget.\n\nOptimal experimental design formalises \"as much information as possible\" using the Fisher Information Matrix and a scalar criterion.","title":"What is experimental design?"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#The-Fisher-Information-Matrix","page":"Theory","text":"For a model y = f(theta x) + varepsilon with Gaussian noise varepsilon sim mathcalN(0 sigma^2(theta x)), the Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) at a single design point x and parameter value theta is:\n\nM(theta x) = frac1sigma^2(theta x) J(theta x)^top J(theta x)\n\nwhere J = partial f  partial theta is the Jacobian. For a design with n measurements at points x_1 ldots x_n, the total FIM is the sum:\n\nM(theta d) = sum_i=1^n M(theta x_i)\n\nThe FIM captures how sensitively the model responds to each parameter at each design point. A larger FIM (in some matrix sense) means more precise parameter estimates.","title":"The Fisher Information Matrix"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#Design-criteria","page":"Theory","text":"A criterion maps the p times p FIM to a scalar measuring design quality:\n\nCriterion Formula Interpretation\nD-optimal log det M Minimise the volume of the confidence ellipsoid\nA-optimal -operatornametr(M^-1) Minimise the average parameter variance\nE-optimal lambda_min(M) Minimise the worst-case parameter variance","title":"Design criteria"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#Ds-optimality","page":"Theory","text":"Often you care about a subset of parameters — say, a rate constant — while others (amplitudes, baselines) are nuisance parameters. Ds-optimality targets the subset by applying a transformation g(theta) that extracts the parameters of interest, then optimising the D-criterion on the transformed FIM via the delta method.\n\nIn OptimalDesign.jl, this is specified with select:\n\ntransformation = select(:k)            # interested in k only\ntransformation = select(:k₁, :k₂)     # interested in two rates","title":"Ds-optimality"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#Bayesian-(pseudo-Bayesian)-design","page":"Theory","text":"An experimental design xi is a collection of measurement points and weights (x_i w_i).\n\nClassical optimal design assumes the parameters are known (or guessed). But the FIM — and therefore the optimal design — depends on the true parameter values, which are unknown before the experiment.\n\nBayesian optimal design (also called pseudo-Bayesian or robust design) averages the criterion over prior parameter uncertainty:\n\nPhi(xi) = int phibigl(M(theta xi)bigr)  pi(theta)  mathrmxitheta\n\nwhere pi(theta) is the prior density and phi is the criterion (e.g., logdet). This produces designs that are good on average across plausible parameter values, rather than optimal only at a single guess.\n\nOptimalDesign.jl approximates this integral by a weighted sum over particles drawn from the prior (or from the current posterior, in the adaptive case):\n\nPhi(xi) approx sum_i=1^N w_i  phibigl(M(theta_i xi)bigr)","title":"Bayesian (pseudo-Bayesian) design"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#The-exchange-algorithm","page":"Theory","text":"Finding the optimal design is an optimisation problem over the space of probability measures on the candidate set. The exchange algorithm (Fedorov 1972, Wynn 1972) solves this iteratively:\n\nStart with uniform weights over all candidates\nAt each step, transfer weight from the worst candidate to the best, using the Gateaux derivative as a guide\nRepeat until convergence\n\nFor batch designs with n measurements, the continuous weights are discretised into integer counts using an apportionment method.","title":"The exchange algorithm"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#The-General-Equivalence-Theorem","page":"Theory","text":"The General Equivalence Theorem (Kiefer & Wolfowitz 1960) provides a condition for optimality. For a D-optimal design xi with transformed dimension q, the Gateaux (directional) derivative phi(xi x) satisfies:\n\nphi(xi x) leq q for all candidates x\nphi(xi x) = q at the support points of the design\n\nIf the maximum Gateaux derivative exceeds q, the design is not optimal and the maximiser indicates which candidate should receive more weight.\n\nOptimalDesign.jl computes and plots the Gateaux derivative via verify_optimality and plot_gateaux.","title":"The General Equivalence Theorem"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#Efficiency","page":"Theory","text":"The efficiency of a design ξ_1 relative to ξ_2 is the ratio of their criterion values, raised to the power 1q:\n\ntexteff(ξ_1 ξ_2) = left( fracdet M(ξ_1)det M(ξ_2) right)^1q\n\nAn efficiency of 0.5 means ξ_1 would need roughly twice as many measurements to match the precision of ξ_2.","title":"Efficiency"},{"category":"section","location":"theory/#Adaptive-design","page":"Theory","text":"In an adaptive (sequential) experiment, the design is updated after each observation:\n\nDesign: choose the next measurement(s) using the current posterior\nAcquire: measure at the chosen design point\nUpdate: incorporate the observation into the posterior via Bayes' rule\n\nThis creates a feedback loop where the experiment learns from its own data. Adaptive designs can outperform batch designs when the optimal measurement locations depend strongly on the (initially unknown) parameter values.\n\nOptimalDesign.jl implements adaptive design using a particle filter posterior. After each observation, particle weights are updated by the likelihood and, when necessary, particles are resampled and jittered to maintain diversity (see Posterior Inference).","title":"Adaptive design"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Plotting","page":"Plotting","text":"OptimalDesign.jl provides plotting functions built on Makie.jl. All plotting functions are exported.","title":"Plotting"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Corner-plots","page":"Plotting","text":"The simplest form takes a result object and automatically shows prior vs posterior:\n\n# From a result object (shows prior vs posterior automatically)\nfig = plot_corner(result; truth = θ_true)\n\nTo compare two results directly (e.g., optimal vs uniform):\n\nfig = plot_corner(result_opt, result_unif;\n    labels = [\"Optimal\", \"Uniform\"], truth = θ_true)\n\ntruth overlays dashed red crosshairs at known parameter values (accepts a ComponentArray or NamedTuple)\nlabels names each posterior in the legend\nparams selects which parameters to show (useful for high-dimensional models; defaults to all)\nhighlight bolds specific parameter labels (auto-set from select(...) when using the result form)\nPass any number of results or Particles arguments to compare them","title":"Corner plots"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Credible-bands","page":"Plotting","text":"Plot model predictions with uncertainty bands. Pass one or more result objects:\n\n# Single result — shows prior vs posterior with observations\nfig = plot_credible_bands(prob, result; truth = θ_true)\n\n# Compare two results — prior panel + one panel per result\nfig = plot_credible_bands(prob, result_opt, result_unif;\n    labels = [\"Optimal\", \"Uniform\"], truth = θ_true)\n\nThe prediction grid is inferred from observations automatically. Pass x_grid to override.\n\nFor vector-valued models, components are displayed as separate columns automatically.","title":"Credible bands"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Convergence","page":"Plotting","text":"Track how parameter estimates evolve over an adaptive experiment. Shows the posterior mean ± 1 standard deviation at each step, with optional true value overlay:\n\nfig = plot_convergence(result; truth = θ_true)\n\n# Show only specific parameters\nfig = plot_convergence(result; truth = θ_true, params = [:k₁, :k₂])\n\n# Plot against cumulative cost instead of observation number\nfig = plot_convergence(result; truth = θ_true, x_axis = :cost)\n\nRequires record_posterior = true in run_adaptive.","title":"Convergence"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Design-allocation","page":"Plotting","text":"Visualise where a batch design places its measurements:\n\n# 1D design variable — stem plot\nfig = plot_design_allocation(ξ, candidates)\n\n# 2D design variables — bubble plot (auto-detected)\nfig = plot_design_allocation(ξ, candidates)","title":"Design allocation"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Gateaux-derivative","page":"Plotting","text":"Check optimality visually — the derivative should touch the bound at support points and lie below everywhere else:\n\n# One-call from arguments\nfig = plot_gateaux(prob, candidates, prior, ξ)\n\n# Or from an OptimalityResult\nopt = verify_optimality(prob, candidates, prior, ξ)\nfig = plot_gateaux(opt)","title":"Gateaux derivative"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Residual-diagnostics","page":"Plotting","text":"After an adaptive experiment, plot observation residuals and cumulative log evidence:\n\nfig = plot_residuals(result.log)","title":"Residual diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Posterior-evolution-animation","page":"Plotting","text":"Record an animation of the posterior evolving as observations arrive:\n\nrecord_corner_animation(result.log, \"posterior_evolution.gif\";\n    truth = θ_true, framerate = 5)\n\nRequires record_posterior = true in run_adaptive.","title":"Posterior evolution animation"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/plotting/#Backend-notes","page":"Plotting","text":"Static figures use CairoMakie (vector graphics, good for papers)\nThe live dashboard in run_adaptive uses GLMakie (interactive window)\nBoth must be loaded in your environment (using CairoMakie or using GLMakie)","title":"Backend notes"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Quickstart","page":"Quickstart","text":"A complete worked example: design an experiment for an exponential decay, acquire simulated data, estimate the parameters, and visualise the results.","title":"Quickstart"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#The-model","page":"Quickstart","text":"An exponential decay with amplitude A and rate k, observed with additive Gaussian noise:\n\ny = A exp(-k  t) + varepsilon qquad varepsilon sim mathcalN(0 sigma^2)\n\nusing OptimalDesign\nusing CairoMakie\nusing ComponentArrays\nusing Distributions\nusing Random; Random.seed!(42) # hide\n\nfunction model(θ, x)\n    θ.A * exp(-θ.k * x.t)\nend\n\n# Ground truth (unknown to the design algorithm)\nθ_true = ComponentArray(A = 1.0, k = 25.0)\nσ = 0.1\nnothing # hide","title":"The model"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#The-acquisition-function","page":"Quickstart","text":"The acquire function is what gets called to make a measurement at a design point x. In a real experiment this would talk to your instrument; here we simulate by evaluating the model at the true parameters and adding noise:\n\nacquire(x) = model(θ_true, x) + σ * randn()\nnothing # hide","title":"The acquisition function"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Setting-up-the-design-problem","page":"Quickstart","text":"A DesignProblem bundles the model, prior uncertainty on each parameter, and what we want to estimate. Here we want to estimate k as precisely as possible, treating A as a nuisance parameter:\n\nprob = DesignProblem(\n    model,\n    parameters = (A = LogUniform(0.1, 10), k = Uniform(1, 50)),\n    transformation = select(:k),\n    sigma = Returns(σ),\n)\n\ncandidates = candidate_grid(t = range(0.001, 0.5, length = 200))\nprior = Particles(prob, 1000)\nnothing # hide","title":"Setting up the design problem"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Computing-the-optimal-design","page":"Quickstart","text":"# create a design with 20 measurements\nξ = design(prob, candidates, prior; n = 20)","title":"Computing the optimal design"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Running-the-experiment","page":"Quickstart","text":"result = run_batch(ξ, prob, prior, acquire)","title":"Running the experiment"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Extracting-estimates","page":"Quickstart","text":"The result carries both the original prior and the updated posterior. Use mean and std to summarise:\n\nusing Statistics\nmean(result)\n\nstd(result)","title":"Extracting estimates"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Visualising-results","page":"Quickstart","text":"Credible bands show how the posterior prediction narrows compared to the prior:\n\nplot_credible_bands(prob, result; truth = θ_true)\n\nA corner plot shows the joint posterior over the parameters:\n\nplot_corner(result; truth = θ_true)","title":"Visualising results"},{"category":"section","location":"quickstart/#Next-steps","page":"Quickstart","text":"Workflows — batch vs adaptive vs design-only\nDefining Problems — all the options for DesignProblem\nBatch Design example — full walkthrough with optimality checking and plots","title":"Next steps"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Batch-Design","page":"Batch Design","text":"Compute an optimal batch design for an exponential decay, compare it to uniform spacing, then acquire simulated data and examine the posterior.","title":"Batch Design"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#The-model","page":"Batch Design","text":"An exponential decay with amplitude A and rate k:\n\ny = A exp(-k  t) + varepsilon qquad varepsilon sim mathcalN(0 sigma^2)\n\nWe want to estimate k as precisely as possible, treating A as a nuisance parameter.\n\nusing OptimalDesign\nusing CairoMakie\nusing ComponentArrays\nusing Distributions\nusing Random; Random.seed!(42) # hide\n\nfunction model(θ, x)\n    θ.A * exp(-θ.k * x.t)\nend\n\nθ_true = ComponentArray(A = 1.0, k = 25.0)\nσ = 0.1\nacquire(x) = model(θ_true, x) + σ * randn()\nnothing # hide","title":"The model"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Defining-the-design-problem","page":"Batch Design","text":"To define a design problem, we need to specify the model, the prior uncertainty on each parameter, the noise level, and which parameters we want to estimate. The prior distributions should cover the plausible range of parameter values. The design is optimised across this full range (Bayesian averaging), not at a single guess.\n\nprob = DesignProblem(\n    model,\n    parameters = (A = LogUniform(0.1, 10), k = Uniform(1, 50)),\n    transformation = select(:k),\n    sigma = Returns(σ),\n)\nnothing # hide\n\nmodel — the prediction function (θ, x) -> y\nparameters — prior distributions on each parameter, using any distribution from Distributions.jl (e.g. Uniform, Normal, LogUniform, LogNormal, Truncated(Normal(...), lo, hi))\nsigma — noise standard deviation. Use Returns(σ) for constant noise, or a function (θ, x) -> σ if noise varies\ntransformation — select(:k) tells the algorithm we only care about estimating k, switching from D-optimal to Ds-optimal design. Omit this to optimise for all parameters equally","title":"Defining the design problem"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Candidate-grid","page":"Batch Design","text":"The candidate grid defines the set of allowed measurements — all the design points where the algorithm is permitted to place observations. Each candidate is a NamedTuple (e.g. (t = 0.1,)). The candidate_grid helper generates the full outer product from named ranges:\n\ncandidates = candidate_grid(t = range(0.001, 0.5, length = 200))\nnothing # hide","title":"Candidate grid"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Computing-the-design","page":"Batch Design","text":"The design function takes the problem, candidates, and a particle-based prior, and returns an optimal allocation of n measurements. The prior (Particles) is a weighted sample from the parameter distributions — 1000 particles is typically enough.\n\nprior = Particles(prob, 1000)\nξ = design(prob, candidates, prior; n = 50)\n\nThe Ds-optimal design concentrates measurements at two extremes — short times pin down the amplitude, long times pin down the rate.","title":"Computing the design"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Checking-optimality","page":"Batch Design","text":"The Gateaux derivative provides a visual check of optimality. It should touch the bound q (the number of parameters of interest) at the support points and lie below it everywhere else:\n\nplot_gateaux(prob, candidates, prior, ξ)\n\ninfo: Discrete vs continuous designs\nThe optimality condition is defined for continuous designs (fractional weights over candidates). In practice, design rounds these weights into integer measurement counts, so the Gateaux derivative may slightly exceed the bound. This is normal — a small overshoot indicates the discrete approximation is close to optimal.","title":"Checking optimality"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Comparing-to-uniform-spacing","page":"Batch Design","text":"How much better is the optimal design than uniform spacing? The efficiency function returns the ratio — a value below 1 means the first design is less efficient:\n\nξ_unif = uniform_allocation(candidates, 50)\nefficiency(ξ_unif, ξ, prob, candidates, prior)\nnothing # hide","title":"Comparing to uniform spacing"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Running-the-experiment","page":"Batch Design","text":"run_batch calls acquire at each design point and updates the posterior via likelihood tempering. The result carries both the original prior and the updated posterior:\n\nresult_opt = run_batch(ξ, prob, prior, acquire)\nresult_unif = run_batch(ξ_unif, prob, prior, acquire)\nnothing # hide","title":"Running the experiment"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Credible-bands","page":"Batch Design","text":"Credible bands show the model prediction uncertainty narrowing from prior to posterior. Passing multiple results overlays them for comparison:\n\nplot_credible_bands(prob, result_opt, result_unif;\n    labels = [\"Optimal\", \"Uniform\"], truth = θ_true)","title":"Credible bands"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/batch_design/#Corner-plots","page":"Batch Design","text":"A corner plot shows marginal and pairwise joint distributions. Passing a single result shows the prior contracting to a tight posterior:\n\nplot_corner(result_opt; truth = θ_true)\n\nPassing two results compares their posteriors directly — the optimal design produces a tighter posterior on k:\n\nplot_corner(result_unif, result_opt;\n    labels = [\"Uniform\", \"Optimal\"], truth = θ_true)","title":"Corner plots"},{"category":"section","location":"#OptimalDesign.jl","page":"Home","text":"Adaptive and static Bayesian optimal experimental design for nonlinear models.\n\nOptimalDesign.jl helps you decide where and how many times to measure in order to learn model parameters as efficiently as possible. It works with any nonlinear model you can write as a Julia function, handles prior uncertainty via particle-based Bayesian averaging, and supports both pre-planned batch designs and fully adaptive sequential experiments.","title":"OptimalDesign.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Features","page":"Home","text":"Batch design — compute an optimal allocation of measurements before acquiring any data\nAdaptive design — sequentially choose the next measurement based on what you've learned so far\nBayesian averaging — designs are optimised across priors (specified through Distributions.jl).\nMultiple criteria — D-optimal (overall precision), Ds-optimal (subset of parameters), A-optimal, E-optimal\nParticle posterior — inference with likelihood tempering and Liu-West resampling\nOptimality verification — via the Gateaux derivative and the General Equivalence Theorem\nBuilt-in plotting — credible bands, posterior distribution and animated evolution","title":"Features"},{"category":"section","location":"#Getting-started","page":"Home","text":"Head to the Quickstart for a minimal working example, or read the Guide for a fuller picture of what the package can do.","title":"Getting started"},{"category":"section","location":"#Related-packages","page":"Home","text":"Kirstine.jl — static Bayesian optimal designs.\nExperimentalDesign.jl — design of experiments.","title":"Related packages"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#Vector-Observations","page":"Vector Observations","text":"When each measurement returns multiple values simultaneously — for example, two spectral channels or two decays observed in parallel — the model is vector-valued. OptimalDesign.jl handles this naturally: the Jacobian becomes a matrix, and the FIM accumulates information from all outputs.","title":"Vector Observations"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#The-model","page":"Vector Observations","text":"Two exponential decays observed simultaneously at time t:\n\nmathbfy = beginbmatrix A_1 exp(-k_1  t)  A_2 exp(-k_2  t) endbmatrix + boldsymbolvarepsilon\n\nFour parameters (A_1 k_1 A_2 k_2), interest in both rates (k_1 k_2).\n\nusing OptimalDesign\nusing CairoMakie\nusing ComponentArrays\nusing Distributions\nusing Random; Random.seed!(42) # hide\n\nfunction model(θ, x)\n    [θ.A₁ * exp(-θ.k₁ * x.t),\n     θ.A₂ * exp(-θ.k₂ * x.t)]\nend\n\nθ_true = ComponentArray(A₁ = 7.0, k₁ = 8.0, A₂ = 1.0, k₂ = 80.0)\nσ = 0.05\nacquire(x) = model(θ_true, x) .+ σ .* randn(2)\nnothing # hide","title":"The model"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#Defining-the-design-problem","page":"Vector Observations","text":"The key difference from a scalar model: model returns a vector and sigma must return a vector of matching length, giving the noise standard deviation for each output component.\n\nWe also add a cost function — longer measurements cost more. The budget keyword (below) will determine how many measurements to make.\n\nprob = DesignProblem(\n    model,\n    parameters = (\n        A₁ = LogUniform(0.1, 10), k₁ = Uniform(0.1, 100),\n        A₂ = LogUniform(0.1, 10), k₂ = Uniform(0.1, 100)),\n    transformation = select(:k₁, :k₂),\n    sigma = Returns([σ, σ]),\n    cost = x -> x.t + 1,\n)\n\ncandidates = candidate_grid(t = range(0.001, 0.5, length = 200))\nnothing # hide","title":"Defining the design problem"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#Computing-the-design","page":"Vector Observations","text":"With budget, the number of measurements is determined automatically from the per-measurement costs — no need to specify n explicitly. The design must balance information for the fast decay (short times) and the slow decay (longer times).\n\nprior = Particles(prob, 1000)\nξ = design(prob, candidates, prior; budget = 100.0)","title":"Computing the design"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#Running-the-experiment","page":"Vector Observations","text":"result = run_batch(ξ, prob, prior, acquire)\nnothing # hide","title":"Running the experiment"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#Credible-bands","page":"Vector Observations","text":"For vector models, plot_credible_bands automatically creates one column per output component:\n\nplot_credible_bands(prob, result; truth = θ_true)","title":"Credible bands"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/vector_observation/#Corner-plots","page":"Vector Observations","text":"With four parameters, the corner plot is a 4×4 grid. Because the two decays share no parameters, the off-diagonal blocks should show approximate independence — the posterior factorises:\n\nplot_corner(result; truth = θ_true)","title":"Corner plots"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/workflow/#Workflows","page":"Workflows","text":"OptimalDesign.jl supports three workflows, each built from the same core functions.","title":"Workflows"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/workflow/#1.-Batch-design-acquire","page":"Workflows","text":"You know the experiment size up front. Compute the optimal allocation, then acquire all data at once.\n\nSpecify the size either as a number of measurements (n) or a total cost budget (budget):\n\n# Fixed number of measurements\nξ = design(prob, candidates, prior; n = 20)\n\n# Or: budget-based — number of measurements determined by costs\nξ = design(prob, candidates, prior; budget = 50.0)\n\nThen acquire and update:\n\nresult = run_batch(ξ, prob, prior, acquire)\n\n# result.prior        — original particle prior\n# result.posterior     — updated particle posterior\n# result.observations  — vector of (x=..., y=...) named tuples\n# result.design        — the ExperimentalDesign used\n\ndesign() returns an ExperimentalDesign — a list of (design point, count) pairs. run_batch() iterates over the design, calls your acquire function at each point, and updates the posterior with all observations using likelihood tempering.\n\nThere is also a convenience form that designs and acquires in one call:\n\nresult = run_batch(prob, candidates, prior, acquire; budget = 50.0)","title":"1. Batch design → acquire"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/workflow/#2.-Adaptive-sequential-design","page":"Workflows","text":"You have a budget and want to choose each measurement based on what you've learned so far. The algorithm loops: design one (or a few) measurements → acquire → update posterior → repeat.\n\nresult = run_adaptive(\n    prob, candidates, prior, acquire;\n    budget = 100.0,       # total cost budget\n    n_per_step = 1,       # measurements per step (1 = fully sequential)\n)\n\n# result.prior        — original prior\n# result.posterior     — final posterior after all observations\n# result.log           — ExperimentLog with full history\n# result.observations  — extracted from log\n\nEach step, run_adaptive calls design() internally to pick the next best measurement given the current posterior. The posterior is updated after each observation, so later measurements are informed by earlier ones.\n\nUse n_per_step > 1 to design mini-batches — useful when switching costs make fully sequential design wasteful.\n\nAdaptive design is most valuable when:\n\nThe optimal design depends strongly on the (unknown) parameter values\nYou can afford the overhead of redesigning between measurements\nYou want to monitor convergence and stop early if the posterior is precise enough","title":"2. Adaptive sequential design"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/workflow/#3.-Design-only-(no-acquisition)","page":"Workflows","text":"Sometimes you just want to compute and inspect a design without acquiring any data — for example, to compare criteria, check optimality, or plan a future experiment.\n\nξ = design(prob, candidates, prior; n = 20)\n\n# Check optimality visually\nplot_gateaux(prob, candidates, prior, ξ)\n\n# Compare to a uniform design\nξ_unif = uniform_allocation(candidates, 20)\nefficiency(ξ_unif, ξ, prob, candidates, prior)","title":"3. Design only (no acquisition)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/workflow/#Choosing-between-workflows","page":"Workflows","text":"Scenario Workflow\nFixed number of measurements, no feedback loop Batch\nBudget-limited, can redesign between measurements Adaptive\nPlanning phase, comparing design strategies Design only\nExpensive switching between measurement conditions Adaptive with switching_cost","title":"Choosing between workflows"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/workflow/#The-acquire-function","page":"Workflows","text":"All workflows that collect data need an acquire function: a callable that takes a design point x (a NamedTuple) and returns an observation y (a scalar or vector).\n\nFor simulated experiments:\n\nacquire(x) = model(θ_true, x) + σ * randn()\n\nFor real instruments, acquire would send commands to hardware and return the measured value. The design point x contains all the experimental settings (e.g., x.t for time, x.dose for concentration).","title":"The acquire function"}]
}
